{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 The central nervous system (CNS) functions as the \ldblquote command center}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \rdblquote  for human behavior, although there are varying views about the precise nature of the commands it issues (in chapter 5 we will discuss two of these views as they relate to motor control). This incredibly complex system, which comprises the brain and spinal cord, forms the center of activity for the integration and organization of the sensory and motor information in the control of movement. Rather than present a complete anatomical and physiological picture of the components of the CNS, we will concentrate on those portions most directly \u173 ?
related to the motor control associated with learning and performing the types of motor skills that are the focus of this book, as discussed in chapter 1.\par }
\pard\plain \s17\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 The Brain\par }\pard\plain \s16\f3\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 The structural components of the brain that are most directly involved in control of movement are the cerebrum, diencephalon, cerebellum, and brainstem. The cerebrum and diencephalon are sometimes referred to as the forebrain. The locations of these components, their subcomponents, and other notable components are illustrated in figure 4.3}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 .\par }\pard\plain \s18\f3\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb200\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs58\f6\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw-2\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 The cerebrum.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
\u8194\'20}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 The }{\f5\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2 cerebrum}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  consists of two halves, known as the right and left }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i cerebral hemispheres,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  which are connected by a sheet of nerve fibers known as the }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i
corpus callosum}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 . Both hemispheres are covered by what is commonly pictured }{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4 in photographs as an undulating, wrinkly, gray-}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 colored surface called the }{\*\cs57\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 cerebral cortex}{\fs20 .}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
 This covering is a\u8239 ?thin tissue of nerve cell bodies called }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1 gray matter.}{\f4\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1
 }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 The gray matter is about 2}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \'d05 mm thick \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 and, if \u173 ?\u173 ?
un\u173 ?folded, would cover about 20 sq ft. The folding results in ridges (each ridge is called a }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2
gyrus}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 ) and grooves (each groove is called a }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i sulcus}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 ). Cortical neurons are either }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i pyramidal }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i cells}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  (based on the shape of the cell body), which are the primary cells for sending neural signals from the cortex to other parts of the CNS, or }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i nonpyramidal cells.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  Underneath the cortex is an inner layer of myelinated nerve fibers called the }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i white matter.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }\pard\plain \s20\f3\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 The cortex of each hemisphere consists of four lobes that are named according to the skull bones nearest to them. The }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i frontal lobe,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  which is the area \u173 ?anterior to the central sulcus and the lateral fissure, contains brain areas that are vital to the control of }
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3 voluntary movement. The }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd1\expndtw3 parietal lobe,}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3  which }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 is the area just posterior to the central fissure and \u173 ?superior to the lateral fissure, is a key brain center for the control of perception and the integration of sensory information. The most posterior lobe of the cortex is the }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i occipital lobe,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  which contains areas important in visual perception. Finally, the \line }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i temporal lobe,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  which is located just below the lateral fissure, plays important roles in memory, abstract thought, and judgment.\par }
\pard\plain \s20\f3\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Several cortex areas are involved in sensory }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 functions. As you can see in }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
figure 4.4, the }{\*\cs57\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2 sen}{\*\cs57\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 sory cortex}{\fs20  areas are located posterior to the central \u173 ?
sulcus. Specific types of sensory information are transmitted via the sensory nerves to the area of the cortex that receives that type of information. Note }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 in figure 4.4 that sensory-specific areas exist for \u173 ?vision, taste, speech, and body (for example, the \u173 ?
somatic sensory area receives pain, temperature, and pressure sensory information). Also note in }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 figure 4.4 the proximity of the sensory and motor areas of the cortex. This proximity is the basis for these areas sometimes being referred to as the }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 sensorimotor cortex.}{\fs20 \par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 Additional areas of the cortex that are important to note are the }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2 association areas,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  which lie adjacent to each specific sensory area in the parietal, temporal, and occipital lobes. The term }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2 association}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  is used to describe these areas because it is there where the brain \ldblquote associates,}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 \rdblquote  or connects together, information from the several different sensory cortex areas. This connecting together involves the integration of various types of sensory information as well as the sensory \u173 ?
information from various parts of the body. In addition, the association areas connect with other cortex areas in ways that allow for the interaction between perceptual and higher-order cognitive functions, such as would occur in a choice reaction time situation where each choice alternative has a different probability of being the correct choice (see Platt\u8239 ?
& Glimcher, 1999, for an example of research showing parietal cortex involvement in this type of choice situation). Because of the activity that occurs in the association areas of the cortex, some neuroscientists consider these areas as the location for the transition between perception and the resulting action.\par }
{\fs20 Four cortex areas are especially involved in the control of movement (figure 4.4}{\fs20  shows these and other areas related to the control of movement as well as specific sensory functions). One area, the }
{\*\cs57\fs20\b\i0\expnd1\expndtw4 primary motor cortex}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4 , which is located in the }{\fs20 frontal lobe just anterior to the central sulcus, contains motor neurons that send axons to specific skel-\line etal muscles throughout the body. This area of the brain is especially critical for movement initiation and the coordination of movements for fine motor skills, such as the finger movements required to type on a keyboard or play a piano. The motor cortex is also involved in the control and learning of }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 postural coordination (see }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Chiou et al., 2018; }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Ioffe, Ustinova, Chernikova, & Kulikov, 2006; Petersen, Rosenberg, Petersen, & Nielsen, 2009). The second area, anterior to the primary }
{\fs20 motor cortex, is the }{\*\cs57\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 premotor area}{\fs20 , which controls the organization of movements before they are initiated and rhythmic coordination \line during movement, thus enabling the }
{\fs20 transitioning}{\fs20  between movements for a skill that involves sequen\line tial movement, such as keyboard typing }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
or piano playing. Research has also shown the importance of the premotor cortex in the performance benefit derived from the observation of actions performed by another person (Buccino et al., 2001}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 ; Holmes & Wright, 2017}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 ). In addition, the premotor cortex has been shown to play a key role in the planning of eye movements and orienting visual-spatial attention (Casarotti, Lisi, Umilt}
{\*\cs59\f8\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 \'88}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 , & Zorzi, 2012). Third, the }{\*\cs57\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2
supple\u173 ?mentary motor area (SMA)}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 ,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  which is located on the medial surface of the frontal lobe adjacent to portions of the primary motor cortex, plays an essential role in the control of sequential movements (see Parsons, Harrington, }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 & Rao, 2005) and in the preparation and \u173 ?orga\u173 ?nization of movement, especially in the anterior portion known as the pre-SMA (see }
{\fs20 \line Cunnington, Windisch\u173 ?berger, & Moser, 2005). More recently, researchers have shown the SMA }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
to play a role, together with other brain regions, in modifying the continuous, bilateral, multijoint movements associated with variable rate pedaling (Mehta, Verber, Wieser, Schmit, & Schinder-Ivens, 2012). Finally, the }
{\*\cs57\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2 parietal lobe}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  has been identified in recent years as an important \u173 ?
cor\u173 ?tical area involved in the control of voluntary movement (Fogassi & Luppino, 2005; Gottlieb, 2007). For example, the parietal lobe plays a significant role in the control of visual and auditory selective attention (}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Gottlieb}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 , 2007; }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Sapountzis, Paneri, & Gregoriou, 2018;}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  Shomstein & Yantis, 2007), visually tracking a moving target (Hutton & Weekes, 2007) and grasping (Rice, Tunik, Cross, & \u173 ?
Grafton, 2007; Rice, Tunik, & Grafton, 2006). Based on an impressive amount of research demonstrating its role in the control of perceptual and motor activities such as these, there is general agreement that the parietal lobe is especially important in the integration of movement preparation and execution processes by interacting with the premotor cortex, primary motor cortex, and SMA before and \u173 ?
during movement (Wheaton, Nolte, Bohlhalter, \u173 ?Fridman, }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 & Hallett, 2005).\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2
An important }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2 subcortical component}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  for the control of movement is the }
{\*\cs57\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw2 basal ganglia}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  (also known as the }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2 basal nuclei}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 ), which are buried within the cerebral hemispheres and consist of four large nuclei: the }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2
caudate nucleus,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  the }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2 putamen}{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2 ,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2
 the }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2 substantia nigra,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  and the }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2 globus pallidus.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  The basal ganglia receive neural information from the\u8239 ?cerebral cortex and the brainstem. Motor \u173 ?
neural information from the basal ganglia goes primarily to the brainstem. A loop of information flow, which is important for motor control, involves the nuclei of the basal ganglia, thalamus, and motor cortex.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 \par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 The basal ganglia play critical roles in the control of movement, especially in the planning and initiation of movement, the control of antagonist muscles during movement, and the control of force (see Pope, Wing, Praamstra, & Miall, 2005). Much of our knowledge of the role of the basal ganglia in motor control comes from research involving people with Parkinson\rquote s disease and cerebral palsy, both of which are basal ganglia disorders }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 (see }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Neumann}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  et al., 2018; }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Ioffe et al., 2006), and strokes affecting the basal ganglia (see Boyd & Winstein, 2004). For instance, in }
{\*\cs57\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2 Parkinson}{\*\cs57\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2 \rquote s disease}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 ,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
 several neural activities associated with the basal ganglia are negatively influenced, with decreased neural information going into the basal ganglia, unbalanced neural facilitation and inhibition interactions, and lower than normal interactions }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 with the motor cortex. Several movement difficulties result from these problems, }{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3
including bradykinesia (slow movements), aki}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 nesia (reduced amount of movement), tremor, and muscular rigidity. People with Parkinson\rquote s disease often have difficulty standing from a sitting position, initiating walking, and writing with a pen. The basal ganglia dysfunction associated with this disease results primarily from the lack of dopamine, which is a neurotransmitter important for normal basal ganglia}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  function. Dopamine is produced by }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 neurons of the }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1
substantia nigra;}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  Parkinson}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \rquote s disease causes these neurons to degenerate, which reduces the production of dopamine.\par }
\pard\plain \s18\f3\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb252\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs58\f6\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw-1\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 The diencephalon.\u8194\'20}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 The second component of the forebrain is the }{\*\cs57\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 diencephalon}{\fs20 ,}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  which lies between the cerebrum and the brainstem. It contains two groups of nuclei, the thalamus and hypothalamus. The }
{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i thalamus}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  serves an important function as a relay \line station, receiving and integrating most of the sensory neural inputs from the spinal cord and brainstem and then passing them through to the cerebral cortex. The thalamus plays an important role in the control of attention, mood, and the perception of pain. The hypothalamus lies just under the thalamus and is the most critical brain center for the control of the \u173 ?
endocrine system and the regulation of body homeostasis, including temperature, hunger, thirst, and physiological responses to stress.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \par }{\*\cs58\f6\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0
Cerebellum.\u8194\'20}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Located behind the cerebral }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 hemi}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4
spheres and attached to the brainstem, the }{\*\cs57\fs20\b\i0\expnd-1\expndtw-4 cerebel}{\*\cs57\fs20\b\i0\expnd-1\expndtw-5 lum}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5  \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 has several distinct parts. The cerebellar}{\fs20  cortex }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2
covers the cerebellum and, like the cerebral cortex, is divided into two hemispheres. Under the cortex lies white matter in which are embedded the\u8239 ?
deep cerebellar nuclei: the red nucleus and the \u173 ?oculomotor nucleus.}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s20\f3\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Sensory neural pathways into the cerebellum arise from three principal regions: the spinal cord, the cerebral cortex, and the brainstem. The motor neural pathways from the cerebellum connect to the spinal cord via the red nucleus and the \u173 ?
descending reticular formation. Output also goes to the motor cortex by way of the central lateral \u173 ?nuclei of the thalamus, a neural pathway known as the cerebello-thalamo-cortico (CTC) path\u173 ?
way.\u8239 ?Finally, there is output to the oculomotor \u173 ?nuclei,\u8239 ?which are involved in the control of eye \u173 ?movements.\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 The cerebellum plays a key role in the execution of smooth and accurate movements. Damage to the cerebellum typically results in clumsy movement. In its role in the control of movement, the cerebellum functions as a type of movement error detection and correction system as it receives a copy of signals about an intended movement sent from the motor cortex to the muscles (often}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  referred to as an }{\*\cs56\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 efference copy}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 ) and compares the motor information with the sensory information it receives from sensory nerves that connect to the cerebellum. This comparison functions in a way that signals to the muscles any needed adjustments to movements already in progress, thus assuring achievement of the intended movement\rquote s goal. The cerebellum is also active in the control of other movement activities such as those requiring eye-hand coordination (see Miall & Jenkinson, 2005), movement timing (see Molinari, Leggio, & Thaut, 2007; \u173 ?
Spencer, Ivry, & Zelaznik, 2005), force control (see Spraker, Corcos, Kurani, Prodoehl, Swinnen, & Vaillancourt, 2012), and posture control (see Ioffe et al., 2006). In addition, the cerebellum is very much involved in the learning of motor skills as it interacts with areas of the cerebral cortex (see }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Honda et al., 2018; }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Ioffe et al., 2006). Researchers are increasingly providing evidence that the cerebellum is also involved in cognition, especially in language, visual-spatial, and working memory processes (Stoodley, 2012), although the specific role played in these processes is }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 only beginning to emerge}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  (see Koziol, Budding, & Chidekel, 2012}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
; Schmahmann, 2019}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 ).}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }\pard\plain \s18\f3\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb260\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs58\f6\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Brainstem.\u8194\'20}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3
Located directly under the cerebral hemispheres and connected to the spinal cord, the }{\f5\fs20\b\i0\expnd1\expndtw3 brainstem}
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3  contains three main areas that are \u173 ?significantly involved in motor control. The }{\f4\fs20\b0\i\expnd1\expndtw3
pons,}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3  which is located at the top of the brainstem, acts as a bridge between the cerebral cortex and cerebellum. Various neural pathways either pass through the pons from the cortex on their way to the spinal cord or terminate as they come from the cortex. The pons appears to be involved in the control of body functions such as chewing, swallowing, salivating, and breathing. It may also play a role in the control of balance.\par }
\pard\plain \s20\f3\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 The second area, the }{\f4\fs20\b0\i medulla}{\fs20  (also called the }{\f4\fs20\b0\i medulla oblongata}{\fs20 ), is like an extension of the spinal cord and serves as a regulatory agent for various internal physiologic processes, such as respiration, in which it interacts with the pons, and heartbeat. In terms of voluntary movement, the\line medulla functions as a site where the corticospinal tracts of the sensory and motor neural pathways cross over the body midline and merge on their way to the cerebellum and cerebral \u173 ?
cortex.\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 The third area of the brainstem involved in motor control is the }{\f4\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2
reticular formation.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  This composite of nuclei and nerve fibers is a vital link in the chain of neural structures that lie between the sensory receptors throughout the body and the motor control centers of the cerebellum and cerebral cortex. Its primary role in the control of movement is as an integrator of sensory and motor neural impulses. The reticular formation appears to have access to all sensory information and can exert direct influence on the CNS to modify activity of the CNS either by inhibiting or increasing that activity, which in turn influences skeletal muscle activity.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 \par }\pard\plain \s18\f3\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb260\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs58\f6\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 The limbic system.\u8194\'20}
{\fs20 An important group of brain }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 structures form what is known as the }{\f5\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1
limbic \u173 ?system}{\f3\fs20\b0\i0 .}{\f5\fs20\b\i0  }{\fs20 It consists of parts of the frontal and temporal lobes of the cerebral cortex, the thalamus and hypothal-amus, and the nerve fibers that interconnect these parts and other CNS structures. This system plays important roles in the learning of motor skills as well as in the control of emotions and several visceral behaviors.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s17\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb250\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 The Spinal Cord\par }\pard\plain \s16\f3\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 The traditional view of the spinal cord is that it is like a telephone cable that simply relays messages to and from the brain. However, we now know that the spinal cord is much more than that. It is a complex system that interacts with a variety of systems and is critically involved in motor control processes.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }\pard\plain \s18\f3\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs58\f6\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw-1\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Spinal cord composition.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
\u8194\'20The two major portions of the spinal cord are the }{\f4\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1 gray matter}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
 and the }{\f4\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1 white matter}{\f4\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1 .}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  The gray matter is the butterfly- or H-shaped central portion of the cord (note figure 4.5). It consists primarily of cell bodies and axons of neurons that reside in the spinal cord. Two pairs of\u8239 ?
\ldblquote horns\rdblquote  protrude from the gray matter, both of which are vital to motor control. The posterior pair of horns, known as the }
{\f4\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1 dorsal horns,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  contains cells involved in the transmission of sensory information. Sensory neurons from the various sensory receptors in the }
{\f3\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 body}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  synapse on dorsal horn neurons. The anterior pair of horns, known as the }
{\f4\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1 ventral horns,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  contains alpha motor neuron cell bodies whose axons terminate on skeletal muscles.\par }
