{\fs19 Brain-Computer Interfaces: Movement by Imagining Moving\par }\pard\plain \s36\f3\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18 A technological advancement called brain-computer interfaces (BCI) has shown exciting potential for helping people whose neurological disorders prevent them from physical movement to regain the capa\u173 ?
bility to move. This computer-based technology takes advantage of the electrical activity in the brain that results from actively imagining the act of moving (recall the discussion in chapter 2 about the use of EEG to record brain electrical activity). As described in a \ldblquote News Focus\rdblquote  article in }
{\f4\fs18\b0\i Science}{\fs18  (Wickelgren, 2003), BCIs read brain waves as a person imagines moving a body part. In some cases, the BCI is part of an EEG skull cap. More recent advances have developed BCIs that can be implanted inside the brain. With training the BCI can provide a means of performing in certain functional activities.*\par }
\pard\plain \s37\f3\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18 The }{\f4\fs18\b0\i Science}{\fs18  article reports several examples of success stories in which patients with various paralysis problems were trained with a BCI to carry out a variety of movement activities, including typing, manipulating a small wheeled robot through a model house, and moving a cursor on a computer monitor to hit icons that communicated statements such as \ldblquote I\rquote m hungry.}
{\fs18 \rdblquote  \par }{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw0 Since the publication of the }{\f4\fs18\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 Science}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw0
 article, many research reports have been published describing humans using BCI devices to perform functional activities. For example, researchers in Austria (Muller-Putz, Scherer, Pfurtscheller, & Rupp, 2005) reported a case study in which a patient was able to train himself in three days to use an implanted BCI so that his paralyzed hand could \u173 ?
maneuver a prosthesis, grasping a small object and moving it from one place to another and then \u173 ?releasing it. Further evidence showing BCI use for grasping was presented by Pistohl and colleagues in Germany (Pistohl, \line Schulze-Bonhage, Aertsen, Mehring, & Ball, 2012). }
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 In addition, research}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 ers from several European }{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-1 countries reported success with two subjects using an EEG-}
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-1 based BCI to drive a real and a simulated wheelchair along a prescribed path (Gal}{\*\cs59\f8\fs18\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1
\'87}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-1 n, Nuttin, Lew, Ferrez, Vanacker, }{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw0 Philips, & Mil}{\*\cs59\f8\fs18\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw0
\'87}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw0 n, 2008). Successful wheelchair control has also been reported by Tsui, Gan, and Hu (2011) in the U.K and Yu et al. (2018) in China.}
{\fs18 \par The continued success of research evidence of the functional use of BCI indicates strong potential for the future benefit of this technique for a wide variety of physical disabilities.\par }
